{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{refimprove|date=September 2014}}
The '''long 19th century''' is a term coined for the period between the years 1789 and 1914 by Russian literary critic and author [[Ilya Ehrenburg]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-tls.co.uk/articles/private/long-centuries/ |title=Long Centuries |publisher=the-tls.co.uk |date= April 29, 2011 |author= Gasan Gusejnov |accessdate= December 23, 2017}}</ref> and British [[Marxism|Marxist]] historian and author [[Eric Hobsbawm]]. The concept is an adaption of [[Fernand Braudel]]'s 1949 notion of ''le long seizième siècle'' ("the long 16th century" 1450–1640).<ref>Braudel, F. (1972). The Mediterranean and the Mediterranean world in the age of Philip II (Vol. 1; S. Reynolds, Trans.). New York: Harper & Row</ref> and "a recognized category of [[History of literature|literary history]]", although a period often broadly and diversely defined by different scholars.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.slu.edu/Documents/arts_sciences/english/Long%2019th%20Century.pdf |title=Long 19th Century |publisher=slu.edu |date= |author= |accessdate= January 11, 2017}}</ref> Numerous authors, before and after Hobsbawm's 1995 publication, have applied similar forms of book titles or descriptions to indicate a selective time frame for their works, such as: S. Kettering, "French Society: 1589–1715 – the long seventeenth century", E. Anthony Wrigley, "British population during the ‘long’ eighteenth century, 1680–1840", or D. Blackbourn, "The long nineteenth century: A history of Germany, 1780–1918".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://treasedademin.files.wordpress.com/2016/11/26032413.pdf |title=French Society: 1589–1715 |publisher=treasedademin |date= |author= |accessdate= January 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geog.cam.ac.uk/people/wrigley/ |title=Department of Geography, Cambridge » Tony Wrigley – British population during the 'long' eighteenth century, 1680-1840 |publisher=Geog.cam.ac.uk |date= |author= |accessdate= January 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showrev.php?id=2349 |title=H-Net Reviews - David Blackbourn. The Long Nineteenth Century: A History of Germany: 1780–1918. New York: Oxford University Press, 1997. xxiv + 578 pp. (paper), ISBN 978-0-19-507672-1. |publisher=H-net.org |date= |author= |accessdate= January 11, 2017}}</ref> However, the term has been used in support of historical publications in order to "connect with broader audiences"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://escholarship.org/uc/item/2k62f464#page-1 |title=Modernity's Histories: Rethinking the Long Nineteenth Century, 1750–1950 (eScholarship) |publisher=Escholarship.org |date= |author= |accessdate= January 11, 2017}}</ref> and is regularly cited in studies and discussions across academic disciplines, such as history, linguistics and the arts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.english.northwestern.edu/about/events/reading-groups-colloquia/long-19thc-colloquium.html |title=Long Nineteenth-Century Colloquium: Department of English - Northwestern University |publisher=English.northwestern.edu |date= |author= |accessdate= January 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bgc.bard.edu/news/events/long-19th-century.html |title=Bard Graduate Center – Symposium—American Material and Visual Culture of the “Long" Nineteenth Century |publisher=Bgc.bard.edu |date= |author= |accessdate= January 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195365870.001.0001/acprof-9780195365870 |title=Arts of the Prima Donna in the Long Nineteenth Century - Oxford Scholarship |publisher=Oxfordscholarship.com |date= |author= |accessdate= January 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brill.com/folklore-and-nationalism-europe-during-long-nineteenth-century |title=Folklore and Nationalism in Europe During the Long Nineteenth Century |publisher=Brill.com |date= |author= |accessdate= January 11, 2017}}</ref>
Hobsbawm lays out his analysis in ''[[The Age of Revolution: Europe 1789–1848]]'' (1962), ''[[The Age of Capital: 1848–1875]]'' (1975), and ''[[The Age of Empire: 1875–1914]]'' (1987). Hobsbawn starts his long 19th century with the [[French Revolution]], which sought to establish universal and egalitarian citizenship in France, and ends it with the [[outbreak of World War I]], upon the conclusion of which in 1918 the long-enduring [[European balance of power|European power balance]] of the 19th century proper (1801–1900) was eliminated. In a sequel to the above-mentioned trilogy, ''[[The Age of Extremes|The Age of Extremes: The Short Twentieth Century, 1914–1991]]'' (1994), Hobsbawm details [[Short twentieth century|the short 20th century]] beginning with [[World War I]] and ending with the [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|fall of the Soviet Union]].
A more generalized version of the long 19th century, lasting from 1750 to 1914, is often used by [[Peter N. Stearns]] in the context of the [[world history]] school.<ref>{{citation|last=Stearns|first=Peter N.|title=World Civilizations: The Global Experience|year=2011|publisher=[[Longman]]|location=Upper Saddle River, New Jersey|isbn=978-0-13-136020-4|edition=6th|author2=Michael Adas|author3=Stuart B. Schwartz|author4=Marc Jason Gilbert|authorlink=Peter Stearns|authorlink2=Michael Adas|authorlink3=Stuart B. Schwartz}}</ref>
In religious contexts, specifically those concerning the [[history of the Catholic Church]], the long 19th century was a period of centralization of [[Papacy|papal]] power over the [[Catholic Church]]. This centralization was in opposition to the increasingly centralized nation states and contemporary revolutionary movements and used many of the same organizational and communication techniques as its rivals. The church's long 19th century extended from the [[French Revolution#Revolution and the Church|French Revolution]] (1789) until the death of [[Pope Pius XII]] (1958).<ref>{{Citation | last = O'Malley | first = John W. | author-link = John W. O'Malley | publication-date = 2010 | year = 2008 | title = What Happened at Vatican II | chapter = The Long Nineteenth Century | edition = Kindle | publisher = Harvard University Press | publication-place = Cambridge | at = locations 1060-1873 | isbn = 978-0-674-03169-2 }}</ref>
